\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Human-wildlife conflict is a growing global problem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Messmer_2000,Treves_n_Karanth_2003b,Nyhus_et_al_2005"

\end_inset

.
 This has implications both for agriculture and for conservation.
 Indeed, some authors have considered the conflict to be human-human conflict
 between agriculturalists and conservation ecologists, rather than between
 farmers and wildlife 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Treves_n_Karanth_2003,Conradie_n_Piesse_2013,Nattrass_n_Conradie_2013"

\end_inset

.
 This imply that any solution to the conflict should address both the agricultur
al perspective and the ecological perspective.
 Although using the general term "human-wildlife conflict" (HWC), this article
 really focus on carnivores and more specifically on predators.
 So the terms "human-carnivore conflict" 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Khorozyan_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

, "farmer-predator conflict" 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Potgieter_et_al_2016"

\end_inset

 will be used interchangeably, with the understanding that "human-wildlife
 conflict" as used here refers not only to carnivores in general (which
 includes scavengers), but specifically to conflict arising from depredation
 of livestock.
 We will be focussing on commercial livestock farming in Namibia, while
 keeping in mind that the same methods could work in other areas with similar
 circumstances and predators.
 The issue of game farming and conflict caused by depredation of valuable
 game animals, is really a separate question and will not be considered
 here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From an ecological perspective it is known that the greatest threat to large
 mammalian carnivores and sharks is direct killing by humans 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Treves_n_Bruskotter_2014"

\end_inset

, an even greater immediate threat than habitat destruction, especially
 in Africa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ray_et_al_2005"

\end_inset

.
 This includes killing of carnivores in retaliation for livestock depredation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ogada_et_al_2003"

\end_inset

.
 Large carnivores, often apex predators, need large home ranges or territories
 to sustain themselves, making them more vulnerable to extinction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cardillo_et_al_2004,Schipper_et_al_2008"

\end_inset

.
 This is exemplified by the cheetah (
\shape italic
Acinonyx jubatus
\shape default
), classified as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Durant_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

.
 In Namibia, the country with the largest surviving population of cheetahs
 in the world 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marker_1998,Marker_et_al_2003b,Durant_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

, an estimated 90% of cheetahs are found on commercial livestock farms (private
 ranches) outside formally protective reserves 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marker_2000,Marker_et_al_2003a"

\end_inset

 with being shot on livestock farms the major cause of death 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Marker_et_al_2010"

\end_inset

.
 In Southern Africa, most of the vulnerable 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Stein_et_al_2016"

\end_inset

 leopard (
\shape italic
Panthera pardus
\shape default
) habitat is found outside protected areas and the major threat to leopard
 survival is direct killing by people
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Swanepoel_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

.
 The same high percentage of habitat outside conserved areas is true for
 tigers, jaguars and snow leopards (Miquelle et al., 1999; Nowell & Jackson,
 1996; quoted in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Dickman_et_al_2011"

\end_inset

).
 With farmers as the custodians of the majority of land in most countries
 of the world, the ultimate survival of many species are squarely in the
 hands of farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A telephone survey by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Van_Niekerk_2010"

\end_inset

 showed that livestock farmers in South Africa claimed a total annual loss
 of R 1 390 453 062 worth of livestock directly to predators 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bergman_et_al_2013"

\end_inset

.
 These losses were unequally distributed with some districts and some farmers
 having much higher losses than the average (see also 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Conradie_n_Piesse_2013"

\end_inset

).
 Similarly, data from the official government-sponsored hunting clubs for
 the period 1979-1987 in the Ceres South district 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Conradie_n_Piesse_2013"

\end_inset

and Cooper hunting club 1976-1981 outside Mossel Bay 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bailey_n_Conradie_2013"

\end_inset

 showed average losses of 1.48 livestock units per farm and 0.94 sheep per
 farm per year, but with highs of up to 114 sheep lost in a single year
 to predators on a single farm.
 In the area around the Waterberg in North-Central Namibia, farmers lost
 on average 3.8% of their calves to depredation annually (US$1370 per farm
 per year according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Stein_et_al_2010"

\end_inset

).
 In a slightly wider area of North-Central Namibia, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Marker_et_al_2003b"

\end_inset

 found that farmers who claimed cheetah problems on average lost 16.7 (2%)
 of their cattle and 18.0 (5.3%) of their small livestock per year for the
 period 1991-1993 and those who claimed cheetahs as not problematic lost
 on average 6.8 (1.3%) of their cattle and 11.5 (4.3%) of their small livestock
 to predators.
 In 1993-1999 the numbers changed to an average of 5.8 cattle lost per year
 by farmers who claimed cheetahs as problematic and 1.2 by those who did
 not consider cheetahs problematic, while they lost on average 8.5 and 12.1
 small livestock respectively.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Lindsey_et_al_2013c"

\end_inset

found the average annual livestock losses reported due to leopards over
 most of Namibia's commercial farm areas to be US$2,644/farm to leopards,
 almost double that reported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Stein_et_al_2010"

\end_inset

 earlier.
 If we keep in mind that we might have a similar uneven distribution of
 livestock depredation between farms as shown by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Conradie_n_Piesse_2013"

\end_inset

 in the Ceres Karoo, the losses of some individual farmers could be very
 high.
 These kinds of losses are not economically insignificant, and a study at
 the Glen Agricultural Institute near Bloemfontein in the Free State, found
 that black-backed jackal (
\shape italic
Canis mesomelas
\shape default
) and caracal (
\shape italic
Caracal caracal
\shape default
) depredation of the Merino and Dorper sheep made it ultimately unsustainable
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bergman_et_al_2013"

\end_inset

.
 In addition to direct losses, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Howery_n_DeLiberto_2004"

\end_inset

 make the point that behavioural changes in livestock because of predation
 risk, can cause significant decreases in production and reproduction rates.
 In the final instance, while everybody benefit from a functioning and biodivers
e ecosystem, the cost of conserving large and sometimes dangerous animals
 is often borne disproportionately by farmers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nyhus_et_al_2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Predators fulfil an important role in functioning ecosystems, and their
 extermination has many unintended consequences, including trophic cascades
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ripple_et_al_2014"

\end_inset

 and extinctions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Estes_et_al._2011,DeCesare_et_al_2010"

\end_inset

, meso-predator release 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ritchie_and_Johnson_2009"

\end_inset

, and savannah ecosystems becoming dominated by more thorny trees and shrubs
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ford_et_al_2014"

\end_inset

.
 Ultimately, the persistence of ecosystem services 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Reiss_et_al_2009,CPW_2014,Grace_et_al_2016*"

\end_inset

 and the stability of ecosystems as such, are dependent on its biodiversity
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cadotte_et_al_2012,Hautier_et_al_2015"

\end_inset

, and there is good reason to believe that predators are a major driver
 of high biodiversity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Terborgh_2015"

\end_inset

.
 E.g.
 the leopard, an apex predator, has been considered as a reliable indicator
 of a healthy ecosystem 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pitman_2012"

\end_inset

.
 Extensive livestock farming is ultimately dependent on sustainable ecosystem
 services for its own survival as a viable economic activity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Bowe_2000"

\end_inset

.
 For both the economic survival of livestock farmers and the persistence
 of relatively species-rich ecosystems on livestock farms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kinnaird_n_OBrien_2012"

\end_inset

, it is important that solutions to farmer-predator conflict be found.
\end_layout

